answers.body_markdown:
Your problem is that your trying to do two jobs with one var `completedTasks`, your using this to decide when all task are done and what the next task is.  These will often not be the same.  Adding another var say called `nextTask` should help here.

Also doing `process.send({});` to kick start each cluster seems a bit hacky.

Instead I just created a new sub function called `addTask` that just gets called in 2 places,  1 inside your cluster init for each cpu, and again when a task has been completed.

In a nutshell, the way messages are sent in Clusters is likely the way you expect, your problem was a logic error instead.

Here is your modified Javascript

    var os = require(&#39;os&#39;);
    var cluster = require(&#39;cluster&#39;);
    
    if (cluster.isMaster) {
        masterCluster();
    } else {
        workerCluster();
    }
    
    function masterCluster()
    {
